Tenet 1: The model does not have a constant mean over time, consider at least 1 order of differencing.

Tenet 2, Part A: Use one difference to correct for the linear trend present in the data.

Part B: Linear trend is present per significant positive autocorrelation at many lags. There also appears to be a seasonal component.

Part C: Lag-1 autocorrelation of once-differenced signal is positive, the series might need another order of differencing (seasonal).

Part D: Series is not over-differenced because lag-1 autocorrelation is about .3 which is much greater than -.5.

Part E: The model does have a time-varying trend, we can expect the model will have two orders of total differencing.

Tenet 3:
The optimal order of differencing here is 1 with a standard deviation of 3.43.

Tenet 4:
Part A: This model has differencing, so far no constant term is needed.

Part B: The model has one order of differencing so far, but we expect an order of seasonal differencing. Thus, still no constant term. If no seasonal differencing term is added, this part of the Tenet needs to be re-evalutated.

Part C: Models with two or more orders (i.e. this model) do not typically include a constant term. Thus, no constant term is required. If no seasonal differencing term is added, this part of the Tenet needs to be re-evalutated.

In [53]: 
def AIC(k,var):
    return 2*k + math.log(var)

def AICc(k,n,AIC):
    return AIC + (2*k*(k+1))/(n-k-1)

def BIC(k,n,var):
    return k*math.log(n)-2*math.log(var)

def CIlow(mean,std,z):
    return mean - z*std
    
def CIhigh(mean,std, z):
    return mean+ z*std

Part D: Series is not over-differenced because lag-1 autocorrelation is about .1 which is much greater than -.5.
